In his weekly address, President Trump expresses his gratitude for the opportunity to honor African American heroes, faith leaders, and entrepreneurs during Black History Month. He highlights his visit to the National Museum of African American History and Culture, acknowledging the contributions of African Americans to American culture, society, and history. The President pledges to continue the march towards justice and freedom for all Americans, regardless of their background. He also mentions his pride in Dr. Ben Carson, who will serve as the Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, and emphasizes the importance of transforming communities and providing access to good schools, safe communities, and high-paying jobs for African Americans. President Trump also addresses the issue of lost jobs and promises to work towards bringing back good-paying jobs to the United States. He concludes by mentioning that he will discuss these issues further in his upcoming Joint Session Address to Congress.